---
import ProgrammingLayout from "../../layouts/ProgrammingLayout.astro";
import ArrowLeft from "@lucide/astro/icons/arrow-left";
---

<ProgrammingLayout title="About Me">
  <article class="py-20">
    <div class="w-full h-full flex flex-col md:flex-row items-center">
      <!-- Profile photo -->
      <div
        class="w-full md:flex-1 h-64 md:h-[60vh] rounded-2xl overflow-hidden ml-12"
      >
        <img
          src="https://assets.joenoseph.co.uk/me/me_002.jpg"
          alt="Profile photo"
          class="w-full h-full object-cover"
        />
      </div>

      <!-- Text content -->
      <div
        class="w-full md:flex-1 h-full flex flex-col justify-start px-12 py-16 md:px-16 md:py-24 overflow-y-auto"
      >
        <div class="flex flex-row justify-between items-start">
          <h1
            class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-6 text-center"
            style="color: var(--color-text);"
          >
            About
          </h1>
          <a
            href="/programming"
            class="text-sm px-4 py-2 rounded-lg transition-colors duration-200 flex-nowrap text-nowrap flex flex-row items-center gap-2"
          >
            <ArrowLeft size={14} />
            Back to Projects
          </a>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            I've spent the best part of seven years as an engineer in the games
            industry, mostly focused on building UI systems and component
            architectures from the ground up. A lot of that time was spent
            figuring out how to make complex interfaces feel simple — whether
            that meant designing reusable component libraries, reworking data
            flow patterns, or just making sure designers and engineers could
            actually work together without stepping on each other's toes.
          </p>
          <p>
            More recently I've been channelling all of that into the web side of
            things. I'm the co-founder of Labbo, a file-transfer and storage
            platform built for the film photography community. It's been a big
            challenge, learning a new set of technologies and applying the
            lessons I learned about shipping polished UI in games, however it's
            incredibly satisfying owning a product end-to-end, especially one I
            am so passionate about.
          </p>
          <p>
            I'm at my best when I can take a vague problem, break it down into
            something concrete, and then just get on with building it. I'm used
            to managing my own workload, writing up detailed task breakdowns
            with honest time estimates, and seeing things through from the
            initial design all the way to iteration based on real feedback. I
            care a lot about the craft of it — clean code, thoughtful
            architecture, and interfaces that genuinely feel good to use.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</ProgrammingLayout>
